english:
  title: Letter to the Scholars of Milyang's Local School
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Summer has come, and all things resume their forms. I wonder how your studies progress, and how Master Choi fares. Since my mourning period ended, I have been driven by famine to lead my household back to Gimhae, unable to spend even a day in peace in my native soil. I could not gather with you and others to discuss the forgotten classics and examine the institutions of our time, to uphold the essential principles that should never crumble within our school. Day and night this weighs upon my heart. Recently, through undeserved grace, I held the position of Lecturer to the Crown, but misfortune brought illness, and I submitted my resignation to the court. When my sickness passes and my body finds rest, I shall hire a boat to return southward and complete what I once envisioned.

    Pondering this deeply, I see that the corruption of rural customs and the blockage of the court's civilizing influence stem entirely from the dimness of learning and teaching in our schools. When teaching shines clearly, the virtues of filial piety, respect for elders, loyalty, and trust become practiced by all. From the school it spreads to the villages, its fragrance penetrates all, and people cannot help but be transformed. The five relationships each find their proper order, and the four classes each settle in their occupations. The customs where every household could be enfeoffed arise naturally from this. How then could depraved and stubborn people who flout the rules arise among us? From this we see that the order or disorder of a single county depends entirely upon its school. Not merely one county—heaven and earth are the same in this regard. Though great and small differ in scale, the principle is one.

    Milyang is an ancient county, its mountains and rivers clear and majestic, deep and mysterious. Its fields are fertile and abundant, its people numerous and prosperous. From its mountains come mulberry, lacquer, bears, tigers, gold, stone, and fine bamboo for arrows. From its waters come water plants, lotus seeds, fish, shellfish, and reeds in plenty. Craftspeople and merchants gather from all directions to trade their wares—it may truly be called a great center of the southeast. Its people are diligent in agriculture and sericulture, quick to pay their taxes and perform their corvée. Should those in authority guide them with benevolence and righteousness, they could be easily transformed and easily governed.

    In the middle period of the former dynasty, when the ruler's grip loosened, unruly elements like Pang Bo and Kye Nyeon spread sedition among the people, colluding with the pirates of Chin Island. They gathered together, but not for long before bringing ruin upon themselves. The world then condemned the county's customs, and later record-keepers who wrote observational records and geographies all said, "Its people love contention," making the county a shame upon heaven and earth down to this day.

    Alas! The states of Qi and Lu were lands of literary culture where the teachings of Confucius and Mencius were preserved. Yet through the ages, many treacherous men and great rebels have seized those lands and raised rebellion. Yet the people of China do not thereby condemn those regions, and when praising the customs of ritual and righteousness, they still place those two states foremost. Why then must our county, because of one rebellion by Pang Bo and Kye Nyeon, a hundred years hence still bear its stain? This reveals how those who compile records lack generosity of spirit and deny people the path to reform.

    Land has no past or present, but people do. The possibility of turning from harshness to kindness surely exists. Then is not the responsibility upon the school? Today, with our sage ruler above and culture flourishing, you gentlemen have all been selected as promising scholars from the fields, donning the robes of scholars, taking positions at the seat of excellence. You should surely embrace the grace of nurturing talent from above and contemplate the methods of transforming hearts below. To clarify the teachings of filial piety, respect for elders, loyalty, and trust as models for your locality, to open the eyes of the foolish masses, to wash away old stains—this is your very task.

    Yet of late the school's regulations have crumbled. Respect between old and young is forgotten. The distinction between new and old is lost. The sound of recitation has nearly ceased. Pride and licentiousness hold sway. Slander reaches the magistrate. Accusations fly among friends. The conduct has become shameful even to woodcutters and shepherds. If this is truly so, then the school destroys custom rather than upholds it. How can we expect the entire county to be moved and awakened?

    Moreover, I hear that courtesans from the entertainment quarters are each assigned to individuals, summoned to lodge in the school dormitories, with some even secretly taken away. And on the days of the Confucian ceremony, the drinking ritual, when honoring teachers with birthday toasts, and at all festive gatherings, music and dancing courtesans are placed before the Hall of Understanding Human Relations. Students in their blue gowns mingle together in licentious songs, wanton dances, crude jests, and indecent laughter, day and night without rest. Those sitting as teachers look on unmoved, content to say nothing, failing to prohibit it. Not only do they fail to prohibit—many actually join in drunken revelry, casting off their garments.

    Alas! This is a great wound upon our moral teachings. A "pure chamber" means to gather one's spirit inward. "Understanding Human Relations" means to illuminate the relationships between people. These names are not meaningless. Yet now they have become places for spreading licentious music and dance—is this not profane?

    In the teaching of the ancient kings, at thirteen one learns music, recites poetry, and dances the dance of sparrows. At fifteen one dances the dance of elephants. At twenty one dances the Great Summer dance. In spring and summer one studies ritual and music. All this was to cultivate purity and clarity. When has it ever been the purpose to gather men and women as the beasts do and call it joy? And as for "banishing the music of Zheng"—was this not what the Master answered when Yan Hui asked how to govern a state? Yet now on the day of the Confucian ceremony, we produce the depraved and corrupting music of Zheng, Wei, and Sangpu near the sacred temple. Can this be right?

    From this we can infer how dimly learning shines. Recently I spoke with wise men of our circle and felt anger stirring in my breast at these things. I said, "Though the customs of the villages are difficult to change suddenly, how can we bear to let the habits of the school go unchanged?"

    Once, when He Fan faced the rebellion of Zhu Ci, he boldly rebuked the scholars of the Six Institutes and prevented them from joining the rebellion. Han Yu praised his courage. An ancient saying goes: "When one man shoots well with the bow, a hundred stand ready to provide arrows." It means that many follow the example. Now if among you there is one who recognizes yesterday's errors and rises above the common current, who corrects his conduct and investigates the learning of human nature, who guides his companions and locality—such a one would be today's He Fan, today's skilled archer. Who can say the school's scholars would not follow like leaves in the wind, all preparing to provide arrows? Who can say the people of the county would not be gradually shaped and transformed until all strive to practice filial piety, respect for elders, loyalty, and trust? Human nature and the patterns of things have not perished since ancient times. The subtlety of transformation moves swifter than shadow following form or echo answering sound. I urge you not to diminish yourselves but to strive.

    Some say to me: "Promoting the ruler's commands is the magistrate's duty. Teaching and clarifying the Way is the school official's task. You have no such responsibility—why speak so persistently? Though your effort is commendable, what good does it bring?"

    I reply: "Though the magistrate and school official conduct their affairs well, they last only through their terms of office, and their successors rarely continue what came before. But I am an elder of this county, a senior in the cause of culture. With you I participate each spring and autumn in the archery ceremony, the drinking ceremony, and the rites honoring the aged. Until my coffin is sealed, every day is a day I may encourage what is right. If there is even one person with a grain of benevolence in their heart, how could they not feel shame and willingly follow after one or two or three such reminders?"

    Having heard this, he said my words seemed reasonable. Therefore I commit this to writing for your consideration. I ask your understanding.
